<body>
<h1>HOME COOKING</h1>
<h2>best way to cook steak</h2>
<div class="first">
<p>Blue Rare   <span class="temp">115F</span><br />
<small> blue rare steak is seared on the outside, to brown the meat without significantly cooking the inside.
<br>Grill Time at 400F   1:30 </small></p>
</div>
 
<div class="second">
<p>Rare  <span class="temp">120F-130F</span><br />
<small>The steak has cool-to-warm red center, and soft, tender texture. This is an excellent choice for leaner steaks like top sirloin or filet mignon that don’t have as much fat to melt.
<br>Grill Time at 400F   2:30 </small></p>
</div>
 
<div class="third">
<p>Medium Rare  <span class="temp">130F-135F</span><br />
<small>Steak will have warm red center – perfect steak texture with a nice brown crust. Cooking to medium rare allows the fat (marbling in the steak) to render and add buttery, rich flavors to your steak. This is the ideal doneness for a juicy, flavorful steak. 
<br>Grill Time at 400F   3:30 </small></p>
</div>
 
<div class="fourth">
<p>Medium Well <span class="temp">135-145F</span><br />
<small>The steak will have a mostly brown center and firm texture. The meat will be drier as water evaporates during the cooking process.
<br>Grill Time at 400F   4:30 </small></p>
</div>

<div class="fifth">
<p>Well Done <span class="temp"> 155F-165F </span><br />
<small>The steak will have no color left, will be very firm and much drier. The meat loses fat and moisture as it cooks, resulting in a dry, tougher texture. We don’t recommend cooking to this doneness.
<br>Grill Time at 400F   6:30 </small></p>
</div>
 
